Dataset - Video Games Sales with Ratings
Name - Name of the game
Platform - Console on which the game is running
Year_of_Release - Year of the game released
Genre - Games category
Publisher - Publisher
NA_Sales - Games sales in North America (in millions of units)
EU_Sales - Games sales in European Union (in millions of units)
JP_Sales - Games sales in Japan (in millions of units)
Other_States - Games sales in Africa, Asia excluding EU and SouthAmerica (in millions of units)
Global_Sales - Total Sales in the world (in millions of unit)
Critic_Score - Aggregate score compiled by Metacritic staff
Critic_Count - The number of critics used in coming up with the Crtic_Score
User_Score - Scores by Metacritics subscribers
User_Count - Number of users who gave the User_Score
Developer - Party responsible for creating the game
Rating - The ESRB(Entertainment Software Rating Board , ratings are EC-early childhood, E-everyone, E10+(everyone 10+, T-teen, M-mature, AO- adult only)

This is a report summary of the Video Games Sales on key aspects.
First, let’s analyse the Customer Preference of Platform based on ESRB Ratings.

#sqldf("select distinct(rating) from df1")
df2 <- df1 %>% filter(!is.na(Rating))
df2 %>% ggplot(aes(Rating, Platform)) + geom_count() + labs(title = "ESRB ratings for various Platforms")

The Platform PS2(Play station 2) was the most popular among Teens. X13, X360, PS3 and PC were Teens other favorites.
Nintendo DS seemed be to be most favourite among E-Everyone.
For E10+(Everyone 10+) category, Nintendo DS, Wii and X360 are the notable favorites.
In E(Everyone) category and across all Ratings, WiiU, PSV, PS4 and DC seemed to be the least favorite.

Overall the critic score of video games was average and there were some outstanding spikes in Platform usage. In 2001 there is a high demand for PS and XB, likewise PC in 2013, PS in 2015 , PAP in 2010 and XBox in 2013.
This may be corresponding to new Game Releases for the Platforms.

I did some research in Wiki to see if these observations were matching up and here is what I find:
-in 2001, XBox was launched and quickly sold out.
-PS was introduced much earlier but 2001 peak was due to the introduction of online gaming.
-Xbox One was released on Nov 2013
-June 2010, manufacturer announced PSP Go would be disconnected outside of NA.
-Late 2013, PC AMD announced Mantle, a low level API with greater performance

Next, let’s analyse the Sales metrics. For this we need to compare the Sales in North America, Europe, Japan, Other countries and Globally for the Releases.

 # have year, Platform , sales, Country
sale <- df1 %>% select(Year_of_Release, Platform, NA_Sales, EU_Sales, JP_Sales, Other_Sales, Global_Sales)
sales1 <- sale %>% gather(key = Region, value = Sales, -Year_of_Release, -Platform)

sales1 %>% ggplot(aes(Sales, color = Region)) + geom_density(adjust = 200) + ylim(0, .004) + labs(title = "Sales Metrics")

  #sqldf("select count(*) from sales1 where region = 'NA_Sales' and Sales > 20")

Overall Globally the maximum sales ranged from $19 - $25 million. In that North America, has the maximum sales ranging between $12 - $20 million, followed by European Union with maximum sales between from $7 - $10 million. In Japan, maximum sales was between $2 - $8 million.

Finally, lets also compare the Gamer’s and the Metacritic’s preferences. Metascores range from 0-100, with higher scores indicating better overall reviews. User score is a 10 point score grading.
a) Games which has high Metascore and low user scores
b) Games which has low Metascore and high user scores.

score <- sqldf("select Name, Critic_Score, User_Score, Year_of_Release, Platform from df1")

score1 <- score %>% filter(!is.na(Year_of_Release), !is.na(User_Score), !is.na(Critic_Score))
#High Critic Score, lower User score
score2 <- score1 %>% filter(Critic_Score > 70 & User_Score < 6) %>% arrange(desc(Critic_Score)) 

#score2 %>% ggplot(aes(x = Critic_Score, y = User_Score, color = Platform)) + geom_point() + geom_smooth(aes(group = 1), method = "lm", se = FALSE)  + facet_wrap(~ Year_of_Release, nrow = 3) + labs(title = "High Critic Score vs. Lower User Score")

#score2 %>% select(Platform) %>% group_by(Platform) %>% count() %>% arrange(desc(n))

score2 %>% ggplot(aes(x = Critic_Score, y = User_Score, color = Platform)) + geom_point() + geom_smooth(method = "lm", se = FALSE, size = 0.5) + geom_smooth(aes(group = 1), method = "lm", se = FALSE, linetype = 3)  + facet_wrap(~ Year_of_Release, nrow = 3) + labs(title = "High Critic Score vs. Lower User Score of Games on Years Released by Patform")

The dotted lines is the aggregate of all scores for Platforms and we see that Games released mainly on X360, PC, and PS3 is hovering on a range of User Score 5-6 for a high Metascore from 70-90 for Games released over the years. Separate line automatically fit the Platforms.

#High User Score, lower Critic score
score3 <- score1 %>% filter(Critic_Score < 70 & User_Score > 6) %>% arrange(desc(Critic_Score)) 

#score3 %>% ggplot(aes(x = Critic_Score, y = User_Score, color = Platform)) + geom_point() + geom_smooth(aes(group = 1), method = "lm", se = FALSE)  + facet_wrap(~ Year_of_Release, nrow = 3) + labs(title = "High User Score vs. Lower Critic Score")

score3 %>% ggplot(aes(x = Critic_Score, y = User_Score, color = Platform)) + geom_point() + geom_smooth(method = "lm", se = FALSE, size = 0.5) + geom_smooth(aes(group = 1), method = "lm", se = FALSE, linetype = 3)  + facet_wrap(~ Year_of_Release, nrow = 3) + labs(title = "Low Critic Score vs. High User Score of Games on Years Released by Patform")

The plot of High User score vs Low Critic score is dense showing that fans of video games have a distinctively different opinion than the game critics!
